{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657615"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:32:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20584"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12504"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents with new-onset headache, scalp tenderness, jaw claudication, and visual disturbances. Her erythrocyte sedimentation rate is 85 mm/hr (0-20). A temporal artery biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histopathological findings is most characteristic of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrinoid necrosis of small vessels with perivascular lymphocytic infiltration","Granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells","Leukocytoclastic inflammation of postcapillary venules with nuclear dust formation","Thrombosis with minimal inflammation and endothelial proliferation","Eosinophilic infiltration of all vessel layers with transmural inflammation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic histopathological finding in giant cell arteritis is \u003Cstrong\u003Egranulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This inflammation typically affects the media and intima of medium and large arteries, with fragmentation of the internal elastic lamina. The inflammatory infiltrate consists of T lymphocytes, macrophages, and the pathognomonic multinucleated giant cells, which are often found at the intima-media junction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis of small vessels with perivascular lymphocytic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of small vessel vasculitides such as microscopic polyangiitis and granulomatosis with polyangiitis, not giant cell arteritis which affects medium and large vessels.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukocytoclastic inflammation of postcapillary venules with nuclear dust formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of cutaneous small vessel vasculitis, not giant cell arteritis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombosis with minimal inflammation and endothelial proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E - While thrombosis can occur as a complication of giant cell arteritis, the primary histopathological feature is granulomatous inflammation, not thrombosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic infiltration of all vessel layers with transmural inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Prominent eosinophilic infiltration is more characteristic of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Churg-Strauss syndrome), not giant cell arteritis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiant cell arteritis predominantly affects adults over 50 years of age, with a female predominance. The granulomatous inflammation can lead to intimal hyperplasia and luminal narrowing, resulting in ischaemic complications such as vision loss if the ophthalmic artery is involved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Giant cell arteritis predominantly affects medium and large arteries, especially branches of the external carotid artery.","Histopathological features of giant cell arteritis include granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells and fragmentation of the internal elastic lamina.","Giant cell arteritis most commonly affects adults over 50 years of age with a female predominance."],"references":["Mitchell RN, Halushka MK. Blood vessels. In: Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, editors. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. p. 485\u2013525."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T10:11:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T10:13:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood